  "body": "## Start with the unit's own status\n\nBefore touching configuration, run `systemctl status <service>` and read the last several log lines it prints inline. Most failures fall into one of a few buckets: the binary path is wrong, a dependency hasn't started yet, a config file has a syntax error, or the process is crashing immediately after start.\n\n## Read the full journal, not just the summary\n\n`systemctl status` truncates. Pull the complete picture with:\n\n    journalctl -u <service> --since \"10 min ago\"\n\nLook for the first error in the sequence, not the last — cascading failures often bury the real cause under several follow-on errors.\n\n## Check dependency ordering\n\nA service that \"sometimes\" fails on boot is often a `Wants=`/`After=` ordering problem rather than a bug in the service itself. Confirm the unit file's dependencies actually match what the service needs to be available (network, a mounted filesystem, another service) before assuming the code is at fault.\n\n## Validate the environment, not just the unit file\n\nServices run under systemd often have a different `PATH`, working directory, and environment than the same command run interactively as a user. If something \"works when I run it myself\" but fails under systemd, diff the environment first — an `Environment=` audit usually finds it faster than re-reading the same unit file a fourth time.\n\n## Keep a personal log of root causes\n\nOver time, patterns repeat: a missing `After=network-online.target`, a relative path that only works from one working directory, a permissions mismatch after a package upgrade. Keeping a short personal note of \"what it turned out to be\" for each incident makes the next one faster to diagnose."
}
